  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency response to extreme food and water insecurity in Alaba and Sankura Woredas of SNNPR</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project aims to save lives, reduce morbidity and protect livelihoods in drought-affected communities through an integrated multi-sectoral food security and WASH intervention. 

Alaba Special Woreda and Sankura Woreda of SNNPR are hotspot priority 1 under Nutrition, DRMFSS and WASH sectors. The project has been coordinated with Regional and Woreda Agriculture and Water offices and is comprised of:
	Emergency seed distribution of haricot bean and fertilizer to 8679  severely food-insecure households (4500 Alaba, 4179 Sankura) in kebeles that have suffered from 80% and above crop failure. Haricot bean has been selected due to its short maturing growth period and it will complement and address the gap in the regional government&#x2019;s planned distribution of maize seed distribution. 
	Complementing the food security and ongoing nutrition interventions with improved, sustainable water supply. Pipeline extensions for deep borehole schemes will target kebeles suffering from critical water shortages (above 5 hour water collection times) and currently receiving water trucking organised by the regional government. Target locations have been coordinated with RWB/UNICEF/ONE WASH activities and IRC and the project addresses the gaps in response.

The project is a follow up to the previous HRF-funded WASH and emergency seed distribution project in Alaba (July-Dec 2015):
	The project was highly successful in addressing critical water shortages with sustainable schemes and the proposed intervention targets the remaining kebeles in severely drought-affected kebeles of Northern Alaba. 
	Due to the failure of Belg and Meher rains in Alaba, post-distribution monitoring showed crop yields were extremely low.  Addressing the ongoing food insecurity is the priority of the proposed follow up project.
The project duration of 9 months is requested in order for PIN to provide support to beneficiaries during crop growth/harvesting and continue hygiene promotion activities.</narrative>
  </description>
